<br>
All 5 epiced mages + shaman<br>
<br>
Four mages had 61 air pet and one had 62 water pet.<br>
We hunted at PoV and PoS.  Mobs drop so fast that puller coudn't keep up with the kills.  Air pet + slow is like &quot;can't touch this.&quot;  Mobs coudn't swing to hit pets because it's always stunned and slowed.  In couple of hours, I gained full level (62 to 63) plus an AA ding.<br>
<br>
If you are from the Seventh Hammer, send me a tell for mage group.  I'm always looking to form one.  I usually send tells to other mages to get to know each other.  I'm surprised that many mages don't know about power of the mage group.  They tend to shy away from it.  It's a shame that they don't know their own power. =(  <br>
<br>
Anyways, in mage group, 61 Air pet rocks.  Think about it... 5 Airpets stunning...  whoa... Epic is a ok addition but tend to get aggro all the time. Plus the procs and stuns don't land well.<br>
<br>
Go and make a mage group! have some fun and make amazing xp.  I hope there are enough mobs out there for ya. =p<br>
<br>
Canvashan Magistic<br>
Arch Mage of the Seventh Hammer <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hurk>Hurk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#333333>(12/2/02 1:43:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Not quite right</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A good healer is required to keep the main tank alive, as they are ideally taking all the damage the enemy deals.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
not really true, specially if your not in PoP.  inside pop, i have seen badly botted druids keep up. so simply a healer is needed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Some even go far as to claim that all other group styles are &quot;gimp&quot; and a waste of time. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
as a foundation of 3 people, there is no better group that is capable of working in any environment. That is the key to the trilogy, they work anywhere, anytime.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is much competition for the role of damage dealer in trinity groups, and usually a surplus of damage dealers. This can be frustrating for the magician, as many players still do not appreciate mage damage output.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
the key to a well played magician is sustaining DPS, while maintaining stratigic resources to deal with emergencies. watching a mage and his pet handle 1 of 3 adds by himself while the second tank and chanter handle the other two is an awesome sight, specially when each of the three is considered a group killer.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Thus pet-centered groups are easier to recruit and easier to sustain than trinity groups. Pet-centered groups have high damage output, and tend to dispatch foes more quickly than trinity groups. And as elementals are the kings of pets, so mages rule pet-centered groups.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
Pet groups have roughly the same damage output as other groups sustained. epic pets and 61+ pets change this pattern, often out damaging all tank classes.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Aggro must be carefully managed, for pets almost never take aggro from a player that is within melee range. This is not the best form of pet-centered group, but is acceptable for very small groups.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I disagree, its dirt simple to control agro in this case, simple stay away from the mob. this is perhaps the easiest pet group for use outside dungeons<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Earth is the simplest and most basic elemental to use in pet-centered groups. Root helps it take, keep, and regain aggro, and elemental root can hold creatures that are otherwise immune to root or snare. The fewer pets and the more aggravating damage dealers there are in the group, the more root will save the day. However, root means that the nearest pet will hold aggro, and other pets generally attack from a closer distance than elementals. Except for warders or charmed creatures, non-elemental pets do not tank well, and will die quickly.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
in mixed company, and when an epic or 61+ pet is avalible earth is the LAST choice for a tanking pet.  its root ability is nice, but no where near the power of agro management that the air and epic have through procing stun and DDs. the earth is for tanking, and even then, only when you lack any support classes.  its only real use now is pet cannibalizing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Fire is an acceptable pet at lower levels with not many pets in the group, as its damage shield is quite impressive. However, depending on the pet mix, it may not have aggro, and its damage shield then is wasted. Post-50 fire pets act like NPC wizards, largely casting spells instead of meleeing, and are probably not a good choice. Indeed, most mages are dubious about the post-50 fire pets in general, although they do have their advocates.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
there are many fire pets, and prior to level 55+ mobs, some of them do quite well.  the pets are wizards, and are born with one of three possible spell loadouts.<br>
1. annul, root, stun, cold, fire, magic nukes.<br>
2. root, stun<br>
3. stun<br>
the fire stuns the wizard level 20 spell Tishan's Clash, which is a 5 second stun + 50DD. When you have a cleric in the group, a buffed stun only pet can hold agro as well as an epic, which is fine for low damage, fast hitting mobs. (shrooms in Fungus grove for instance) Its fire shield is only slightly better than a mages. so is mostly saving on pet maintenance.<br>
<br>
the 61+ fire should be avoided, they did not change its spell load out.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Air elementals stun, and where applicable this can be valuable against casters and hard hitting mobs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Air is by far the best tanking pet post 60, and is slightly better than the epic in most cases.  although not as good at keeping agro, or dealing damage, it does heal on its own much faster (like 3% per tick) as well as enrageing(as do all 61+ pets) enrage is a awesome way for a pet to really punish several adds before it dies, and almost always give the mage 12 seconds to decide what to do. The air pet as main tank is simply the best choice.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Water elementals are another good choice, especially post-50 when they act as rogues and can backstab the enemy. If the group contains a necromancer, you may decide to fear-kite, and the post-50 water elementals are ideal for this. If the group has enough pets and earth elementals can be avoided, post-50 is an excellent choice for killing the mob more quickly when it turns to flee.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
water should only be used in a group with another source of main tank and agro holding.  they do not hold agro at all compared to a epic or air pet. their back stab is a nice DPS upgrade, but if you find its not landing at least 50% of the time, dump it for a diffrent pet.  in a raid, a buffed water pet will out damage real rogues, but in a exp group you are not throwing raid level buffs on to enable this DPS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Epic is an awesome pet, especially pre-60. A pet-centered group with multiple epics is a sight to behold. The epic has high damage output, stuns, and an innate damage shield. If root is not necessary, the epic is almost always the best choice if available. Its only downside in these groups is that it is more costly and time consuming to replace the epic. Against high DPS mobs, it may be a good idea for the epic mage to memorize a second pet, just in case.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
outside of 61+ pets, the epic is bar none the best. its often overlooked proc is 141cold based damage, a class of damage mages do not get, also its casted stun+DD simply add punishment to the mix.  there is no pet that can hold agro better except, perhaps a pure stun fire pet.  the obvious advantages of the epic make the fire not even an option. Epic chaining is not advised, it is much betterto fully equip the epic, and find target it can kill with a single bar of health.  long term you will find your kill rate remains constant.  it is best to couple the epic with any form of healing, and let the mage himself unleash his full DPS on a target. having the best possible damage shield, that stacks with the (small) wizard damage shield is also a great source of added DPS<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Beastlords are a welcome addition to any pet-centered group. Not only are warders comparable to elementals in their toughness and damage output, but the lord brings slows, buffs and heals to the group. However, the warder usually takes aggro from the elementals, and costs more time and mana to replace.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
a beastlord will take less damage than his warder, so its perferable when adding a beastlord (unless another healer is not avalible) to allow the Beastlord to tank for all the pets, and use water pets for extra DPS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Enchanters bring a great deal to a pet-centered group. Besides the obvious mind candy, they can slow and mezz adds. Charmed mobs make very powerful pets, often dwarfing summoned pets for damage and hitpoints. However, this can be risky. As mentioned previously, it can be difficult for pets to take aggro from players, and enchanters are aggromaniacs. Therefore earth elementals may be best, especially if the enchanter is not used to this group style. Enchanters also have a relative weak summoned pet, which can be useful, but tends to take aggro from elementals.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
anyone that uses a earth in conjunction with a chanter needs to seek therapy.  unless the mob is stun immune, a epic or air pet will tank and hold agro well beyond the scope of a earth's root. Most enchanters i know end up being the puller, so forgo their pet to make this easier. A dire enchanter is the best of both worlds, and can often find a pet of equal offensive power and tanking ability of a mages pet. charmed pets are best in larger groups that have plenty of others that can immediatly handle a broken charm, but at 61+ and PoP, the charm benifit far outwieghs its risk. directly doubling a groups EXP gain is not unheard of.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Wizards are a good addition to pet groups, as long as they can avoid aggro. They have a variety of fast, efficient, and hard nukes. Although they have a summoned sword pet, it is useless in pet groups as it takes aggro and dies almost instantly.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Wizards are the measure of agro holding.  a tank that can hold agro through a chain burning wizard is a keeper for sure, and where i have done all my pet testing (and player testing) the wizard pet will work along side mage pets in some zones.  the idea that certian pets will always take agro is false.  its largely zone/mob dependant.  Mobs are coded generally to attack the &quot;nearest&quot; target. this makes pets get agro in oder of proximity to the mob.  since epics tend to be the largest, and have the largest hit radius, other pets get inside their range and take agro. The deep is a good example of a place where cleric and wizard pets can simply never be used with mage pets.  they will always gain agro.  where as umbral plains, hammer and sword almost never gain agro, even when sent to attack first.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Druids bring nukes, heals and buffs. Unless there are a lot of pets or the groups is fear-kiting, they probably should leave Boo Boo Bear at home, since he tends to take aggro from the stronger pets. In some zones, animals can be charmed to great effect.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
if you were to ask the best duo partner for a mage, a druid would top the list.  bringing almost all the utility you could want except for slow and haste. boo boo isnt a pet, hes a role playing aid.  2dps sustained with max haste isnt a pet.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Shaman are a great addition to nearly any group. Slow is an absurdly powerful ability, heals are nice, and their combat buffs are second to none. Their wolf pet tends to take aggro from stronger pets.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
once mobs get high DPS a druid is lost to a shaman as a mages best friend.  bringing heals, slow/haste, his own pet and nice buffs that tend to affect the pets better than players, there is no better single choice for a partner in the high end game.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> <br>
Clerics, while not as valuable as in trinity groups, are also welcome. They can easily sustain an elemental tank without risking aggro. Death is always a possibility, and ressurection a welcome relief. They have a hammer pet, but it always takes aggro from stronger pets and dies quickly.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
clerics are not the best choice of the three healing classes, they are the worst. their only advantage is allowing you to fight harder targets, which you generally stay away from when EXPing anyway.  however, PoP and CT have larger uses for them, as their specialization and CH tend to allow for higher staying power, and longer fight times before med breaks.  (very useful for inserting into a camp for instance)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
In general, healers reduce the need to replace pets, and so allow the pet owners to devote more of their effort to dealing damage as God Intended: by casting a vengeful rain of fire and steel upon their foes (being naughty in His sight).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
never forget to fully arm and armor your pet if you have a steady healer in your group.  spending the time to summon and equip a pet with armor and focuses (for the extra ac and hitpoints) adds at least 5% to any pets staying power.  not bad for 5 minutes work.  dont forget at 61+ to share your new weapons with others' pets as well.  all classes will wield at least one of the new summoned weapons.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
In general, melees are not welcome in pet-centered groups. Pets almost never take aggro when a player is within melee range of a mob, so player melees negate the whole premise of this strategy. There are some exceptions. With the right AA, high level Rangers can sustain significant damage through archery alone, and can also contribute to the group by pulling. Although the details are not well understood, Monks appear to have some kind of aggro reduction factor, and one or two monks can share aggro with epic and air pets so long as the elementals outnumber the monks and root is not used. Rogues might be useful when fearkiting, but are otherwise unwelcome in pet-centered groups. Bards can mezz and charm, but must be careful to maintain their distance from the melee.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Melees being added is only good if you have a source of healing.  PCs, even of lower level, tank significantly better than pets.  they may not deal nearly as much damage though. (specially true of lower level paladins/SKs) If a monk or rogue is levels above the casters, they will still most likely tank better than a pet, as well as adding a higher DPS than a pet.<br>
<br>
one thing often overlooked is the value of a mage in and of itself.  at any level, a mage can duplicate the DPS of a rogue without a problem, unless the mobs being fought are both fire and mage resistant (in which case the mage should be moving on anyway)<br>
<br>
Some mages play poorly and others are diamonds in the rough. Like druids, mages where the early solo class. often recommended to those that wanted to solo, or that lacked time to really group. this leads to a great many people without grouping skills. <br>
My pet mage for instance, almost never remembers to self buff. he is only concerned with mana regeneration, not pool size. Often when the crap hits the the fan, i hear his oom long before I'm at half with my wizard. this ignoring of pool and defensive abilities has often cost him his life. Never ignore things, because they seem &quot;trivial&quot;  it will often cost you more than the small trouble it takes to do them.<br>
<br>
Not mentioned was the decoy pet. often over looked, it is perhaps the best tank a mage can get until either a epic or 61+ pet.  having the same innate damage shield as a fire pet, a nice proc, and being lower level, tends to get the pet hit more.  however, its coded with a high ac, so mitigates a great deal of damage as well as having the same HP as an earth pet. <br>
this is perhaps the best pet for when you want a mob to &quot;kill itself&quot;. this pet also seems to have the best tuant skill of all.  you can almost be garunteed that a &quot;tuanting attacker master&quot; is followed by the mob ignoring everyone but the Decoy.  I have not had a chance to test its DPs since hte pet changes, since my pet mage achived his epic shortly before that. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=erun>Erun</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#333333>(12/2/02 1:57:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Very nice post Balanz</span><hr size=1> The last few months I have been spending a lot of time in Sebilis with a 56 Wizard and 54 Enchanter.<br>
<br>
We zone in, make pet, look around for any other non-melee LFGs, summon a pet, and head down.  While we are killing frogs, we keep an eye out for other non-melee LFGs.  If one comes along, wiz absconds, invites, and I CoH.  <br>
<br>
Make sure that when you make clear to any potential LFGer that you invite that it is a 'Pet-Centered' group (as the esteemed Balanz has dubbed it).  Many players are uncomfortable with this type of group, or they have a melee friend who they are expecting to invite once they are in the group and someone leaves, so it is good to be up-front about it.  It seems that the more desirable of non-melee classes for traditional groups (chanter, cleric, shaman) are hesitant to engage in these groups.  It is probably due to the fact that they never have to spend more than 5 minutes LFG in any zone, so if you dont tell them up front that they are being invited to a pet-centered group, they may arrive, look at unconventional group makeup, and disband and go LFG again (sometimes without saying anything).<br>
<br>
With another wiz and a druid we were able to take and hold Disco2 (although it was pretty tense).  With just wiz and chanter we can easily take and hold gang and exit.  We could probably take and hold chef, bar, and dpath (sorry if these camp nicknames are server specific), but for the camps with more dense spawns it is nice to have a healer along cause in dungeouns you are going to get hit, if even only for a few seconds while you run past the engaged pet or when a mob pops on top of you.  Having a evac'er is nice when things get a bit sketchy, but that is always true I suppose.<br>
<br>
The main problem we have, which isnt a huge problem, is that occasionally you die and have no rezzer.<br>
<br>
As for PoP zones, I have tried that only once when Calebe invited me to his PoP group (mage, mage, shaman, and monk for pulling).  The two mage pets were easily destroying mobs once slowed, and with only the three of us in the group, we were taking out mobs faster than many full groups are able to.<br>
<br>
As was pointed out, melees are strictly forbidden with the possible exception of Rangers, particularly the AA archery enabled rangers.<br>
<br>
As to the mechanics of aggro amongst multiple pets, I have long desired a mechanism which would allow us to exercise some control over which pet has aggro.  The weakest pet seems to always take aggro.  The idea of shrunken pets having an effect on aggro is novel, and hope to hear more about it and will do some research on it myself.  Has anyone had any success with having one pet's 'taunt' on while the others are not?  I havent noticed much of an effect of /pet taunt in these situations, but maybe you have.  Maybe if one of the pets is equipped with the new proc'ing weapons they can hold aggro, although I doubt it.<br>
<br>
I think once you are comfortable with these type of groups you will have opened up a larger array of options for camps and groups, so it is worth the investment of investigating it for yourself if you have not already done so.<br>
<br>
I would like to take an opportunity to point out one tactical aspect that you may find helpful in circumstances.  When a pet is tanking a mob and another mob (say a wanderer or a spawn) starts pounding on one of your groupmates,  target the new mob, use /pet back off and /pet attack in quick succession and in many cases the pet will successfully engage the add while the original target will follow and attack the pet, allowing the palyers to get out of harms way.  As you know it sometimes takes several attempts to get this to work, as the orginal mob will be attacking and re-agroing you try to get him on the new mob.  /pet hold may help in this matter.  Of course the vast majority of you who have read this far already know this.<br>
<br>
While I am writing about this I may as well point out another subtle tactical point, useful in some situations to those without Pet Discipline AA ability.  When you park a pet with /pet guard here, he will return to that point when his hate list is cleared, either by all mobs being dead or by issuing the /pet back off command.  However, the pet tends to return to his parking spot in a leisurely fashion.  If you are having trouble extracting your pet from a mob, it is sometimes helpful to issue the /pet follow command while it is engaged and get a decent distance away from him and then issue the /pet back off command.  The pet will typically move away from the mob at a higher speed, increasing the chances that he gets away from the mob before being aggro'd again.  In my experience, the Air pet is the easiest pet to extract from a tanking situation, however in single-pet pet-centered groups, Earth pet is typically the most desirable, due to his root proc and his large HP pool.<br>
<br>
Another underused and fascinating tactic involves Dyzil's Deafening Decoy pet.  While he has a low HP, his DS is very powerful, and his AE taunt is unique and effective.  Using these aspects of the Dyzil pet, and the fact that aggro is not transferred to one who heals a pet, it is sometimes very entertaining to send a Dyzil pet into a room with many spawns, and allow the healer(s) to chain-heal the pet while the mobs destory themselves on your pet's DS.  Make sure other members of the group allow plenty of time for the mobs to hurt themselves in this fashion before casting offensive spells on them to finish them off.  I do this in the chef room of sebilis (5 strong frogs densley packed) among other locations.  This tactic should not be attempted in PoP zones, as even multiple clerics would have a hard time keeping Dyzil alive against multiple PoP mobs.<br>
<br>
I may have rambled a bit toward the end here.<br>
<br>
Erun<br>
60 Mage<br>
SBoW<br>
E'Ci<br>
