ence my preference for earth)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Slow is an absurdly powerful ability.  A 66-75% slow is essentially the same as multiplying group hitpoints and healing by 3-4 times, i.e. double, then double again.  A single shaman makes a far greater difference to almost any group than a single druid.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hurk:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> clerics are not the best choice of the three healing class<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I have had much better luck partnering with clerics than druids.  They almost never let the pet die, and are workmanlike in rooting adds.  They seem better able to work in a limited space, which is my preference.  I find that people that play clerics are very attentive to details.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hurk:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Melees being added is only good if you have a source of healing. PCs, even of lower level, tank significantly better than pets.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->But they introduce requirements the pet-centered group seeks to avoid.  Healing pets generates almost no aggro for the healer, so that all pet groups is more relaxing for the healer than keeping a player alive, especially in the absence of a slower.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hurk:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  If a monk or rogue is levels above the casters, they will still most likely tank better than a pet, as well as adding a higher DPS than a pet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->When building these groups, I tend to group with lower levels.  I teach them that I personally and mages generally are awesome to group with, and they remember later me in their career with group invites.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hurk:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Like druids, mages where the early solo class. often recommended to those that wanted to solo, or that lacked time to really group. this leads to a great many people without grouping skills.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Grouping <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">is</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> a skill, and all players of every class are well advised to master it their entire careers.  While pre-61 I was able to solo fruitfully at every level, I was also building groups.  Players <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">do</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> have reputations, which are discussed in-group while recruiting <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>/LFG</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hurk:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Not mentioned was the decoy pet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I have not tried it in groups, only for farming greens.  I suspect at 62nd level it is too late in my career to use decoy in groups.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Erun:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  (chanter, cleric, shaman) are hesitant to engage in these [pet-centered] groups<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Again often true, but this why I recruit below my level.  The mere presence of <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">any</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> adequate shaman, cleric, or enchanter adds more to the group than holding out for a higher level of the same class.  Lower levels are more impressed by the mobs the group is able to hunt, for them they are grouping <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;up.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  And again, they return the favor with group invites later.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Erun:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The two mage pets were easily destroying mobs once slowed, and with only the three of us in the group, we were taking out mobs faster than many full groups are able to.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is what I have observed as well.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Erun:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The weakest pet seems to always take aggro<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Seems that way to me mostly.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Erun:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Has anyone had any success with having one pet's 'taunt' on while the others are not? I havent noticed much of an effect of /pet taunt in these situations, but maybe you have.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Uhm nopers, not me.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Erun:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I would like to take an opportunity to point out one tactical aspect that you may find helpful...in many cases the pet will successfully engage the add while the original target will follow and attack the pet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes, I omited a section on dealing with adds, it is forthcoming.  Again, I find earth useful for this purpose.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Erun:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  /pet hold may help in this matter.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->It does.  My hot-key is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>/pet hold, /pet back off</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which first, causes the pet to ignore its hate list, and second, to empty it. The near absolute control it gives you is well worth the AA.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Brin:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  my experience has been that a pet group in non-PoP zones is the best xp grinding group there is.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Of course, the vast majority of my experience with these in pre-PoP.  I have had maybe 60 hours of PoP play since my new job.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Kegulik:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Yes, while buffing a beastlords pet is prohibitively expensive, they also get near-cleric level heals. Just have the beastlord play pet-cleric. It is what it sounds like-the warder tanks, and the beastlord merely slows and heals.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This has been my experience so far.  However, pet-clericking tends to be rather mana intensive, while I favor having longer fights that use less mana.  The lords I have grouped with have adapted either by pulling their warders out of each fight for a little while, letting the elemental take some beatage, or alternately, have their warder sit out some fights entirely.  I try to use between 10-40% mana per fight, ideally no more than 15%, keeping down time to a minimum.  I can accomplish this by chaining pets if need be, but this is not much of an option for beast lords.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Kegulik:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Mind if I cross-post it to the beast boards?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Please do.  I thought about posting it there, but I have not always been well received, and I had little specific to say to beastlords other than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Please join us.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
