 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.jackntracie.com/images/gojirax.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tipop>Tipop</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#333333>(12/3/02 1:13:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.telocity.com/~Tipop2000/minimark.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pet Groups</span><hr size=1> Someone else mentioned this earlier, but I think it bears repeating, as mages are probably not as commonly aware of this as beastlords.<br>
<br>
When you have two or more pets on a mob, aggro rules change.  They *can* hold aggro over PCs in melee range, assuming the pets are generating more aggro.  If you have three or four pets, and the melees wait a few seconds before stepping in and do not taunt, they can fight the entire battle without getting hit once.<br>
<br>
Beastlords notice this more than necros and mages because we are a melee class, rather than a caster.  When two or more beastlords group, they rarely take much damage themselves even though they are melee'ing along side their warders.<br>
<br>
Thus there is no need to completely exclude a warrior or paladin or whatever as long as you meet the requirements of two or more pets. <p><br><center><img src="http://members.telocity.com/~Tipop2000/notherkrag.jpg" width="500" height="200" border="0" usemap="#nothermap"><map name="nothermap"><area alt="Fury of Faith" coords="31,157,152,187" href="http://members.telocity.com/~Tipop2000/fury"><area alt="Tipop's Homepage" coords="186,157,321,187"  href="http://members.telocity.com/~Tipop2000/"><area alt="Kraggan's Magelo Profile" coords="342,157,465,186" href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=120506"></map></center>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kivulinyamaa>KivuliNyamaa</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#333333>(12/3/02 2:20:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pet Groups</span><hr size=1> First let me say that I'm a big fan of mages and quite frankly, class friction between mages and my own class, Beastlord, is silly when we complement each other so well. This thread is a great show of what we can do united.<br>
<br>
I must second Tipop. I've fought in many pet-only groups and always, if there are two or more pets, I have never taken aggro from the pets. Try a group with a mage and five beastlords if possible on your server. You want to talk about &quot;assembly-line&quot; mob compacting? Yeah. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
What we bring to a pet group is varied. We have mana regen buffs for the casters and decent stat buffs for the pets themselves. If aggro is centered on our warder, not only does he tank well but we can also heal him with extreme mana-efficiency; negating the need for chaining pets. We're not nukers, and we can't DoT as well as a shaman or druid, but we can add our own melee damage into the mix to make up for it.<br>
<br>
And if you want loads of sparks, if you've a mage that can summon the wrulan sword and fist of ixiblat, hand a couple to the warder to watch him proc three different spells. That's a lot of doom.<br>
