adin or whatever as long as you meet the requirements of two or more pets.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->While I do not doubt your observations, I know it is not as simple as this.  For example, I had a pet group, two elementals, shaman's dog, and charmed animal, and still the melee took almost all the damage.<br>
<br>
The rule has to be more complex.  It is as if there are some multipliers or bonuses involved.  Stun has high hate, and so is more likely to take aggro.  I think monks have a hate reduction factor to keep them from taking aggro all the time with their low delay.<br>
<br>
There might be similar factors with both or either of lord and warder.<br>
<br>
But it is definitely <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">not</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> as simple as any two pets and any melee.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Tipop:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Beastlords notice this more than necros and mages because we are a melee class, rather than a caster.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->No, I am well aware of who gets aggro in melee when you mix pets and PCs.  For one thing, it frustrates me not to be able to invite young guild melees into my pet groups.  I have a great deal experience watching PCs get all the beat down, even with multiple pets.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Tipop:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  When two or more beastlords group, they rarely take much damage themselves even though they are melee'ing along side their warders.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Perhaps lords have a hate reduction factor, like monks do, and for the same reason, low delay.  Also, perhaps warders have a bit more hate than other pets.  Thus the lowered hate of the lord exposes the extra hate of the warder, and that explains what you see.<br>
<br>
I bet you if you had a water elemental and warder, instead of two warders, the warder would take aggro.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Khati Sha:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I must second Tipop. I've fought in many pet-only groups and always, if there are two or more pets, I have never taken aggro from the pets.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->It <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">must</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> be more complicated than that.  In elemental-heavy groups, I see different results.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Khati Sha:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Try a group with a mage and five beastlords if possible on your server. You want to talk about &quot;assembly-line&quot; mob compacting? Yeah.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I am more likely to see the opposite: five mages and a lord.  Wonder which kills faster?  Fast enough, either way.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hobbess:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Thus if the beastlord pet dies its an even smaller loss.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->It takes more time and mana to bring them up to snuff I thought.  As I understand it, warders take a fair number of buffs to be ready.<br>
<br>
Post-50 elementals take 400 mana to summon, and are pretty ready for action straight out of the box.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hobbess:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  As has been mentioned by fellow beastlords all pets on a given mob share a collective taunt.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That is an interesting hypothesis.  Still, it needs some rounding out.  Why don't lots of elementals hold aggro from most melees?<br>
<br>
There are some other factors at play here.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tipop>Tipop</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#333333>(12/3/02 8:28:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.telocity.com/~Tipop2000/minimark.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The Collective Taunt is the Vanguard of the Pet's Army!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I will pay more attention to this possibility. The rule-of-thumb &quot;The pet with the least hitpoints is attacked first&quot; has been correct for me over 90% of the time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Actually, I think it's whatever pet is lower level... but of course, that generally means the same thing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What I observed was this: one or two monks sharing aggro with stun pets that outnumber them. But under all other circumstances, it seems as if any PC in melee range gets aggro over pets.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
It depends if the melee's are taunting, if they wait a few seconds before going in, and if they have procs or cast spells that add a lot of hate.  Shadow Knights, for example, almost always grab aggro from a number of pets because they can't seem to stop casting their high-taunt DoTs and taps.  (Force of habit, of course.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>While I do not doubt your observations, I know it is not as simple as this. For example, I had a pet group, two elementals, shaman's dog, and charmed animal, and still the melee took almost all the damage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Perhaps the melee was taunting, or doing one of the other things mentioned above?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I bet you if you had a water elemental and warder, instead of two warders, the warder would take aggro.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Nope, I've done that before too.  As I recall, it was me and a mage at the kodiak caves in Great Divide.  I never got hit once, and my gator very rarely got hit, and the mage was upset because his pet kept taking all the damage.  He was a couple of levels lower than me, which explains it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It takes more time and mana to bring them up to snuff I thought. As I understand it, warders take a fair number of buffs to be ready.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That used to be the case, back when we had to level-buff the warder.  Now it's just summon warder, haste, and proc... costs roughly the same mana as a mage summoning elemental, burnout, and conjuring a weapon. <p><br><center><img src="http://members.telocity.com/~Tipop2000/notherkrag.jpg" width="500" height="200" border="0" usemap="#nothermap"><map name="nothermap"><area alt="Fury of Faith" coords="31,157,152,187" href="http://members.telocity.com/~Tipop2000/fury"><area alt="Tipop's Homepage" coords="186,157,321,187"  href="http://members.telocity.com/~Tipop2000/"><area alt="Kraggan's Magelo Profile" coords="342,157,465,186" href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=120506"></map></center>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hobbess007>Hobbess007</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#333333>(12/3/02 8:37:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The Collective Taunt is the Vanguard of the Pet's Army!</span><hr size=1> As to why you seldom see your pets taking aggro away from melee's, can't say that I know.  Just as one possiblity to mention, should make sure the melee PC isn't taunting, just one thought though I'm sure it likely isn't the cause.  Have to make sure the power cord is plugged in when the computer stops working neh?<br>
<br>
As for a mana count on the beastlord pet:<br>
<br>
Going to use post 60 spells for reference as those are the ones I trust as being most up to date, particularly with the semi-recent changes to the method beastlords summon their pets by.<br>
<br>
Level 62 pet Spirit of Arag 400 mana casting time 10 sec<br>
Level 63 pet hase Arag's Celerity 450 mana casting time 6.5 seconds<br>
Level 63 pet proc Spirit of Rellic 50 mana 3 second casting time<br>
(though numbers are pretty much the same for all pet procs)<br>
<br>
Total mana 900 and 19.5 seconds to be fully operational<br>
<br>
Now since I couldn't through a semi cursory examination find a list of Magician spells I'm basing these spells off of EQ Casters realm, so if they are wrong, I apologize.<br>
<br>
Level 62 Mage pet Servant of Marr 400 mana 12 second cast time<br>
Level 62 pet haste Burnout V is 150 mana and 6 second casting time<br>
Total mage mana = 550 and 18 seconds<br>
<br>
<br>
If you want to compare raw time for readiness than yes mages have a few seconds over mages, and a substatial amount of conserved mana after hasting.  <br>
<br>
So if in a group the pets are expected to die, then the mage pets are faster and more mana efficent to replace.<br>
<br>
But if the pets are to live, and it is better to have all of the pets alive, not only for speed of damage being dealt, but in smaller groups simple security of having 2 pets instead of 1.<br>
<br>
Beastlord spell Healing of Sorsha has a 9 second cast time and heals 2100 health for 425 mana.  Comparatively Planer Renewl for mages heals 1250 hp for 400 mana in 7.25 seconds.  Clearly hear the advantage is in the beastlord.<br>
<br>
The level 62 beastlord pet has 3500 hp, enough to last long enough to be healed.  The question then becomes &quot;is it more efficent to have the MT pet alive all the time or let it die and simply recast?&quot;  If a 62+ pet deals ~65 DPS(a low number as I understand it), the 18 seconds that the mage pet is out of the fight costs the group 1170 points of damage and the beastlord pet 1267.5 points of damage.  If the beastlord pet is tanking mobs such that the healing spell is capable of keeping it alive atleast another 18 seconds, by casting a 400 mana spell -&gt; 1267/400 = 3.something.  A decent ratio.  And for those 18 seconds the mage is saved 550 mana on a new pet that they are now free to spend on nukes or malosi.<br>
<br>
Yes I am making a fair number of assumptions, I do however think they are reasonable ones.  In the pet group if a pet dies, that usually means the mob changes direction, something that reduces the damage of the other pets.  The damage of the collective pet group drops while the pet is being replaced.  I think it is more efficent both mana and time wise to try to maintain the MT pet, at least if it is a beastlord pet.  If the group does expect the pets to frequently die then yes the mage summons are faster and less mana intensive. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showMessageRange?topicID=8009.topic&start=1&stop=20>1</a> <b>2</b> <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showMessageRange?topicID=8009.topic&start=41&stop=55>3</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showPrevMessage?topicID=8009.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showNextMessage?topicID=8009.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=40><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/addReply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"><a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.threadControl?topicID=8009.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/unread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=8009.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=8009.topic>Unsubscr